library(readr)
census <- read.csv("ill_school_data.csv")

(A) Describe the data. Who is in this data set? What are some of the interesting characteristics of this data set?

This dataset contains Illinois student information such as grade, gender, age, personal preferences regarding physical activity, education aspirations, and conservation issues, and hours of homework, sleep, and technology use. This data includes questions that range from being strictly informational or numerical to moderately opinionated; this introduces the possibility of personal biases in the survey results.

(B) Perform the appropriate test to test the null hypothesis that handedness is independent of favorite season vs the alternative hypothesis that there is some dependence.

completecensus <- na.omit(census)

table <-table(completecensus$Handed, completecensus$Favorite_Season)

chisq <- chisq.test(table, correct=TRUE)
## Warning in chisq.test(table, correct = TRUE): Chi-squared approximation may be
## incorrect
chisq
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table
## X-squared = 24.323, df = 12, p-value = 0.01838

H0: An Illinois student’s handedness and favorite season are independent variables. There is no association between these two variables. HA: An Illinois student’s handedness and favorite season are dependent variables. There is an association between these two variables.

(B) Do you think it is ok here to remove the blanks? Explain why or why not.

I think it is ok to remove blank responses to the handedness and favorite season questions because having a student not answer whether they are right- or left-handed would not be useful in testing whether handedness is independent of their favorite season.

(B) Explain your reasoning for the test you chose and state your conclusions.

I decided to run a chi-square test of independence because this procedure tests for independence between two categorical variables. The variables in this study are handedness and favorite season. With a p-value of 0.01838, we reject the null hypothesis at an alpha of 0.05, suggesting that there may be an association between Illinois students’ handedness and favorite season.
